Vehicles.

A vehicle is a rideable motor vehicle — a car the player can mount and drive across the map, with real momentum and, if you want it, the ability to run enemies down. Walk onto a parked vehicle, press the interact key, and the player gets in; the movement keys then steer and drive it until they get out. Its pedal-powered cousin, the bike, is covered in its own topic.

How a vehicle works.

A parked vehicle sits on its tile playing a quiet beacon loop so the player can find it. Pressing interact on its tile gets the player in, and pressing interact again gets them out. While driving, most of the player's usual abilities — the camera, the hook, jumping, pausing, quitting, the speed step, the spier, and turning — are suspended until they get out.

Steering and speed are separate controls. Pressing a movement direction turns the vehicle to face that way — left, right, and forward or back on topdown and 3d maps — and announces the new heading. Speed is held rather than stepped: hold the accelerator to build up through gears zero to twenty, hold the brake to slow down, and release both to coast gradually to a stop. The vehicle has momentum, so it gains and loses speed over time instead of changing instantly, and the engine note rises in pitch as it goes faster. The vehicle moves one tile per step.

A horn sounds for as long as the horn key is held and stops when it's released. If the vehicle is set to hit other entities, driving onto an enemy's tile runs them over and deals the vehicle's attack damage; with that option off, the vehicle passes over everything harmlessly. The vehicle has health and can be damaged by weapons and explosives; when its health runs out it's destroyed and the driver is thrown out.

Crashing.

Running into a wall or the map edge depends on speed, exactly as it does for a bike. In a low gear (one through ten) the vehicle bumps — a stuck sound plays and it reverses and stops. In a high gear (eleven through twenty) it crashes: the crash sound plays, the driver is thrown out, and the vehicle is destroyed. The faster you drive, the more a wall costs you.

How a vehicle differs from a bike.

Both machines are mounted and dismounted by pressing interact on their tile, suspend most of the player's abilities while ridden, bump at low speed but crash and are destroyed at high speed, and carry health that weapons can whittle down. The differences:

A vehicle is motor-powered with momentum. It builds and sheds speed gradually through its accelerator and brake, moves one tile per step, rises in engine pitch as it speeds up, can be set to run enemies down for damage, and sounds a horn. It has no terrain restriction.
A bike is pedal-powered with instant gear changes, covers several tiles per step, refuses rough terrain, plays surface-specific rolling sounds, carries a bell and a wall-proximity radar, and can't harm anything. See the bikes topic.

Vehicle fields.

The vehicle form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and y (and z on 3d maps) — the tile the vehicle is parked on.
Health. How much damage the vehicle can absorb before it's destroyed.
Maximum attack. The damage the vehicle deals to an enemy it runs over, used only when hit other entities is on.
Base speed. The base movement timing in milliseconds. The current gear divides into this, so a lower base speed is a faster vehicle overall. Defaults to 1000.
Accel speed. Milliseconds between each step up in speed while the accelerator is held — a lower number builds speed more quickly. Defaults to 50.
Brake speed. Milliseconds between each step down in speed while the brake is held — a lower number slows the vehicle more quickly. Defaults to 25.
Vehicle sound (a folder name from the vehicle sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the beacon, motor loop, turn, horn, hit, stuck, crash, death, and hurt clips. Pick none for a silent vehicle.
Hit other entities while moving (checkbox). When checked, the vehicle damages enemies it drives onto; when unchecked, it passes over them harmlessly.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the vehicle sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the motor clip of the highlighted theme, hold control and press L to hear its beacon clip, and hold control and press H to hear its death clip.

Authoring vehicles by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a vehicle is: vehicle x y health damage speed accelspeed brakespeed vehtype hit. On 3d maps a z follows y: vehicle x y z health damage speed accelspeed brakespeed vehtype hit. The numeric fields are whole numbers, hit is the literal word true or false, and the vehicle sound must match a vehicle sounds folder name or the word none.
